Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: New Mauritius Hotels, Zenith Bank

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-08-05T16:17:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-05/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-new-mauritius-hotels-zenith-bank.html
FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  declined
for the ninth day, the longest losing streak since at least
January 2004, retreating 1.9 percent to 763.84, the lowest since
Sept. 7, by the 4 p.m. end of trading in Windhoek.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index slid 1.7 percent to 1,997.85 by
the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , the biggest retreat since
Sept. 28, 2009. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index
dropped for a fourth day, slumping 1.5 percent to 23,397.44 by
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement
for the bourse. Kenya’s All-Share Index weakened 0.4 percent to
66.12 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index rallied for the second day, increasing 0.7
percent to 1,184.88 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  New Mauritius Hotels Ltd. (NMH)  , the country’s biggest
leisure company by market value, declined 3 rupees, or 3.1
percent, to 95.5 rupees, the lowest close since May 2009. The
Port Louis-based company said its third-quarter loss through
June widened to 133 million rupees ($4.7 million) from 94.5
million rupees a year earlier.  Zenith Bank Plc (ZENITHBA)  , Nigeria’s largest lender by
market value, slumped 71 kobo, or the maximum daily limit of 5
percent, to 13.59 naira, the lowest close since Oct. 29 as
concern about economic recoveries in the U.S. and  Europe  curbed
demand for frontier-market assets.  “There is a global pessimism towards equities that is
overwhelming the positive trend in Nigerian banks,” Adesoji
Solanke, a Lagos-based analyst with  Renaissance Capital , said by
phone today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
